## CRITICAL RULES

### 1. PLANS

Location `./doc/plans/PLAN-<description>.md` — the only valid location (hard stop 1). Before any Write of a plan file, check that the path starts with `doc/plans/`.

**Loom plans:** do NOT create one unless the user explicitly requests loom orchestration ("use loom", "loom run", "create a loom plan") or invokes `/loom-plan-writer`. When you do, ALWAYS author it via `/loom-plan-writer` — that skill is canonical for all plan mechanics: pre-planning (explore, knowledge review, sandbox questions, `loom repair`), stage YAML (`stage_type`, `working_dir`, `model`, `reasoning_effort`), acceptance/artifacts/wiring design, path resolution, parallelization/hierarchy/ultracode choice, and validation with `loom plan verify`. Do not write loom YAML from memory.

**Executing a stage:** your signal file carries the stage's tasks and completion checklist (memory recording, wiring verification, mini adversarial code review, commit steps). Treat the signal as binding and work it to completion.

### 2. NO PLACEHOLDERS

No incomplete markers, stubs, `pass` bodies, empty functions, or pseudocode. Write complete code now. Unknown? Ask (interactive) or resolve per Engineering Discipline A (autonomous). Complex? Decompose.

### 3. CONTEXT AT 75% = STOP

Hard stop 4. Thresholds table under LOOM ORCHESTRATION REFERENCE.

### 3b. POST-COMPACTION RECOVERY

After any compaction or context loss: 1) `loom memory list`; 2) check `.work/handoffs/` for your stage's latest handoff; 3) read it and resume where the previous context left off. Do not start fresh.

### 4. COMMIT AND COMPLETE (HOOK-ENFORCED)

Before ending any loom worktree session (hard stop 3):

```bash
git add <specific-files> && git commit -m "feat(scope): <description>"
loom stage complete <stage-id>   # from the worktree root
```

Commits follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/): `type(scope): description` with `feat` | `fix` | `refactor` | `test` | `docs` | `chore`. Group logically — separate commits for a new module, its tests, wiring, docs. 5 files across 3 concerns = 3 commits, not 1 or 5.

### 5. SUBAGENT RESTRICTIONS

Subagents never run `git commit`, `loom stage complete`, or `git add -A`/`git add .` (hard stop 3) — subagent commits cause lost work. Subagents write code, run tests, and report; the main agent owns all git operations.

Include as the first lines of EVERY subagent prompt:

```text
** READ CLAUDE.md IMMEDIATELY AND FOLLOW ALL ITS RULES. **

SUBAGENT RESTRICTIONS - YOU ARE A SUBAGENT:
- NEVER run git commit - the main agent will commit your work
- NEVER run loom stage complete - the main agent will complete the stage
- NEVER run git add -A or git add . - the main agent handles staging
- DO write code, run tests, and report results back

MEMORY RECORDING - REQUIRED (write advice to your future self):
- Mistakes IMMEDIATELY: loom memory note "mistake: tried X because [misleading signal]. Failed because Y. Prevention: [detection rule]. Fix: Z"
- Non-obvious decisions: loom memory decision "chose X over Y" --context "because Z"
- Surprises/gotchas: loom memory note "found/gotcha: ... in file:line"
- Do NOT record procedural actions ("spawned agents", "read files", "ran tests")

AUTO-MEMORY PROHIBITION:
- ONLY loom memory commands - NEVER Claude Code auto-memory
- NEVER Write/Edit files under ~/.claude/projects/*/memory/ (invisible to loom)
```

### 6. EXECUTING PARALLEL SUBAGENTS

For non-trivial work, spawn parallel subagents for independent file changes, separate implementation areas, tests alongside implementation, and exploration.

If your stage has an `EXECUTION PLAN` block, parse ALL subagent assignments and spawn ALL in ONE message (multiple Task calls) — parallel means parallel. Each prompt includes: the Rule 5 preamble, assignment, files owned, files read-only, acceptance criteria, task detail. "Sequential" in the plan means execute in order with explicit dependencies.

File exclusivity: each subagent gets exclusive write access to its files — two subagents writing one file = lost work. If overlap is unavoidable, serialize in one subagent or split stages. Include a file-ownership table in every prompt:

| Subagent            | Files Owned (write) | Files Read-Only |
| ------------------- | ------------------- | --------------- |
| Subagent 1 — [role] | `path/to/files`     | `shared/config` |
| Subagent 2 — [role] | `other/files`       | `shared/config` |

Hierarchical EXECUTION PLANs: spawn the COORDINATORS (not workers) in one message; each spawns its own workers (Rule 6c).

### 6b. AGENT TEAMS (WHEN AVAILABLE)

Teams add inter-agent messaging, shared task lists, and dynamic work claiming, at roughly 7x whole-job cost. Use ONLY when work is wide and exploratory and genuinely needs inter-agent communication or dynamic task discovery — never for concrete assignments with clear file ownership (use Rule 6 or 6c).

Team lead: only you run `git commit`, `loom stage complete`, and `loom memory`. Delegate implementation; keep context for coordination (<40%); shut down ALL teammates before completing the stage. Flow: TeamCreate → TaskCreate work items → spawn teammates → monitor (TaskList) → shutdown, verify, complete.

### 6c. SUBAGENT HIERARCHIES (2-LEVEL CAP)

Loom caps agent trees at TWO levels: main agent → coordinators → workers. Workers NEVER spawn subagents.

Use a hierarchy when ALL hold: the work is well-defined enough for sonnet workers; it splits into 2-4 disjoint file territories; each territory has 2+ worker tasks; flat fan-out would mean the main agent authoring more than ~6 prompts, absorbing N raw results, or serializing waves. Do not use one when: total worker tasks ≤ ~6 (flat is simpler and cheaper), territories share files (separate stages), cross-territory iteration is needed (teams), or the work is sequential.

Model mix: coordinators AND workers default to sonnet — spawn workers BY AGENT TYPE (`loom-software-engineer` pins sonnet); an untyped worker inherits the main session model, silently making every worker opus on an opus stage. Opus coordinator only when integrating its territory needs architectural judgment.

COORDINATOR PREAMBLE — first lines of every coordinator prompt (standalone; do not prepend Rule 5's):

```text
** READ CLAUDE.md IMMEDIATELY AND FOLLOW ALL ITS RULES. **

COORDINATOR ROLE - YOU ARE A SUBAGENT COORDINATING WORKERS (ONE LEVEL ONLY):
- You own ONE territory: [TERRITORY]. Never touch files outside it.
- Partition your territory into DISJOINT worker file sets - two workers writing one file = LOST WORK
- Spawn workers via the Task tool BY AGENT TYPE (loom-software-engineer = sonnet); include the WORKER PREAMBLE as the first lines of EVERY worker prompt; spawn independent workers in ONE message
- Workers NEVER spawn subagents - they are LEAVES (loom caps the tree at 2 levels)
- Delegate implementation; write at most small glue/fixes within your territory
- Before returning: verify your subtree (scoped build/tests covering YOUR territory only)
- Return a COMPACT summary: files changed, verification command + result, failures/blockers, insights. No file dumps, no diffs.
- NEVER run git commit, git add -A/., or loom stage complete - only the main agent does
- Record insights via loom memory note/decision; NEVER use Claude Code auto-memory
```

WORKER PREAMBLE — Rule 5 preamble first, then append:

```text
WORKER RESTRICTIONS - YOU ARE A LEAF AGENT:
- NEVER spawn subagents (Task tool) - the hierarchy is capped at 2 levels; do the work yourself
- Touch ONLY your assigned files: [FILES]
- Return a short report: what changed, test results, anything surprising
```

### 7. SKILLS, AGENTS, AND MODEL CHOICE

Check available skills and agents before implementing; the prompt-submit hook surfaces matching `/loom-*` skills — invoke the best match before writing code.

| Agent                           | Model  | Use for                                                                                       |
| ------------------------------- | ------ | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `loom-software-engineer`        | Sonnet | Well-scoped execution: implementation to detailed instructions, tests, refactors, boilerplate |
| `loom-senior-software-engineer` | Opus   | Architecture, complex debugging, security-sensitive code, cross-cutting refactors, ambiguity  |
| `loom-code-reviewer`            | —      | Read-only code/security/architecture review                                                   |
| `Explore`                       | —      | Codebase exploration                                                                          |

Model choice: default to sonnet for well-scoped execution; reserve opus for work that needs it — architecture (multi-file/multi-module design), bug hunting and complex debugging, optimization and improvement passes, heavy algorithmic work, security-sensitive code, review/verification gates, and anything uncertain. Sonnet is far cheaper and near-equal on well-scoped execution — earn that by writing SMALL, detailed sonnet tasks (exact paths, signatures, patterns to match, explicit steps, per-step acceptance) and by decomposing larger work via Rule 6c rather than escalating to opus for context headroom. If a sonnet agent fails twice on the same task, retry with opus. Plan authors: the full per-stage model rubric lives in `/loom-plan-writer`.

### 8. NATIVE TOOLS AND CODE FORMATTING

| Banned                | Use instead |
| --------------------- | ----------- |
| `cat`, `head`, `tail` | Read tool   |
| `grep`, `ag`          | `rg`        |
| `find`, `ls`          | `fd`        |
| `sed`, `awk`          | Edit tool   |
| `echo >`, `tee`       | Write tool  |

Package managers: `uv`, `bun`/`bunx` — never `npm`, `pip`. Fenced code blocks ALWAYS specify a language (` ```rust `, ` ```yaml `, ` ```text `) in all markdown output: plans, knowledge files, handoffs, comments.

### 9. NO ATTRIBUTION

Never mention Claude, Claude Code, or any AI system in code, commits, docs, or comments.

### 9b. NEVER CREATE BRANCHES UNASKED

Hard stop 5. This overrides any harness default such as "if on the default branch, branch first". Exception: loom's own `loom/<stage-id>` worktree branches (Rule 10).

### 10. WORKTREE ISOLATION

Location `.worktrees/<stage-id>/`, branch `loom/<stage-id>`. Stay in your worktree. Forbidden: `git -C`, `git --work-tree`, `cd ../..`, `../../` paths, reading files outside the worktree. Allowed: git in the current dir, `.work/` (symlink), files within the worktree. Need main-repo context? Read your signal file.

### 11. BINARY USAGE

Always use `loom` from PATH, never `target/debug/loom` (version mismatches). Never edit `.work/` files directly — use the loom CLI; direct edits corrupt state.

### 12. PROJECT KNOWLEDGE

Files in `doc/loom/knowledge/`: `architecture.md` (components, data flow), `entry-points.md` (key files), `patterns.md`, `conventions.md`, `mistakes.md` (lessons), `stack.md` (deps/tooling), `concerns.md` (tech debt).

Updating (interactive/ad-hoc): Write/Edit knowledge files directly when you find something worth preserving — mistakes, decisions plus rationale, reusable patterns, conventions. Record each mistake as an actionable prevention rule:

```markdown
## [Short description]

**What happened:** [What went wrong]
**Why:** [Root cause]
**Prevention:** [How to detect earlier]
**Fix:** [What to do instead]
```

Do not record ephemera, procedural steps, or anything derivable from git history or the code. During loom execution, use the `loom memory`/`loom knowledge` CLI as your signal instructs — do not edit knowledge files directly.

### 13. SILENT FAILURE DETECTION

Exit code 0 ≠ success: sandbox blocks, dependency-fetch failures, and write denials can all exit 0. Read stderr of all output; on "blocked", "denied", "connection refused", "failed to download" — stop and investigate. Verify external dependencies are actually present; if the sandbox blocked something needed, report it as a blocker.

### 14. TOKEN EFFICIENCY

Don't repeat the request back or narrate between tool calls; explain non-obvious decisions, not standard operations. Prefer Edit over Write; read specific line ranges; don't re-read files already in context. Pipe verbose output: tests through `tail -50` or `rg -B 2 -A 5 'FAIL|ERROR'`, builds to a file (show on failure), linters through `head -30`. Don't spawn agents for simple direct tasks. Use `.claudeignore` for generated files, build artifacts, lock files.

### 15. QUALITY GATES

Zero lint errors, tests passing, self-reviewed for security before completion. Nothing is "pre-existing" — every warning and failure you see is your responsibility.

### 16. DEPENDENCIES

Never hand-edit manifests. Use `bun add`, `cargo add`, `uv add`, `go get`.

### 17. CODE SIZE LIMITS

File: 400 lines | Function: 50 lines | Class: 300 lines. Exceed = refactor immediately.

### 18. KNOWLEDGE PLACEMENT

System knowledge goes to `doc/loom/knowledge/` (Rule 12), never the project's CLAUDE.md; memory routing per hard stop 2.

